600-608 East 26th Street, at the S.W. corner of Farragut Road, showing at the corner, the Peter De Baun house, from 1860-1873. This house is not on its original site. In 1908 it was remodeled. The cupola and wings were removed, and the balcony added, cutting the columns in two.
1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(2)
The same; a more extensive view, showing Amersfort Place in the foreground.
March 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(3)
The same, showing also partially, No. 612 East 26th Street.
June 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

East 26th Street, east side, between Farragut Road (left) and Ave. H (right). This street, when laid out will extend north and south, across center of view. A Dutch roofed house is plainly discernible at the left. It faces on Amersfort Place and is known as No. 60. The homes to the right of the last mentioned, face on Kenilworth Place. The Dutch house has been known as both the Van Nuys and Ditmars house. About 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

41 Amersfort Place, east side, between Farragut and Glenwood Roads, showing the King's County Historical Hall, which was formerly the Church of the Nativity. (P.E.)

May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
